transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
# Medical Research Interview - Session Begin

Thank you for taking the time to meet with me today, Emily. I really appreciate your willingness to participate in this research. 

Before we dive in, I want you to know that this is a safe space to share your experiences openly and honestly. Everything you tell me is confidential and will help us better understand maternal health and fertility experiences.

I've reviewed your health history, and I can see you've had quite a journey. I'd like to start with some foundational questions and then move into more specific areas about your reproductive health and experiences with healthcare.

---

**Let me begin with a few opening questions:**

**1. How are you doing today? Is there anything on your mind that you'd like to mention before we get started?**

Take your time, and please feel free to share whatever feels relevant to you.

---

*[I'm settling in with my notepad, maintaining an open, attentive posture, ready to listen carefully to your response]*

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily settles back in her chair, offering a small but genuine smile*

Oh, thank you for asking. I'm doing okay, all things considered. It's been a bit of an emotional rollercoaster lately, if I'm being honest.

*She pauses, tucking a strand of hair behind her ear*

So, I'm an elementary school teacher—I teach third grade at Lincoln Elementary here in town. I've been doing it for about twelve years now, and I really do love working with the kids. It keeps me busy and gives my days a lot of structure and purpose. My husband, Mark, he works in manufacturing at one of the plants nearby. We've been married for about eight years now.

*Her expression becomes a bit more thoughtful, with a hint of wistfulness*

We have two wonderful children already—both boys, ages 6 and 4. They were both born without any major complications, which I'm grateful for. But... well, that's part of why we're here, I suppose.

*She shifts slightly, her tone becoming more vulnerable*

For the past year, we've been actively trying to have another baby, and it just hasn't happened. It's been harder than I expected, especially since the first two pregnancies came fairly easily. We had one miscarriage about eight months ago, and that was really difficult—both physically and emotionally.

*She looks up at you*

So we're exploring our options now, including potentially looking into fertility treatments. It's all a bit overwhelming, but I'm trying to stay hopeful.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily nods thoughtfully, her expression becoming more reflective*

Yes, of course. Well, as I mentioned, I have two successful pregnancies behind me, and then the more recent miscarriage.

*She takes a breath*

My first pregnancy was with my oldest, Jacob. I was 30 at the time, so about eight years ago now. I remember finding out I was pregnant—it was actually a bit of a surprise, honestly. We weren't necessarily *not* trying, but we weren't actively planning either. I took a home pregnancy test on a Saturday morning because I just had this feeling, you know? And there it was—positive. I was shocked but thrilled. I called Mark right away, and we just... we were so excited.

*A small smile crosses her face at the memory*

That pregnancy went smoothly. I had the typical morning sickness in the first trimester, some fatigue, but nothing serious. I delivered Jacob vaginally without complications when I was 31. It was a good experience overall.

*She continues*

Then with my second son, Lucas, I got pregnant when Jacob was about two and a half. That one was planned. I was 34 then. Again, it was pretty straightforward—found out with a home test, confirmed it with my OB-GYN. That pregnancy was also uncomplicated, and I had another successful vaginal delivery at 35.

*Her expression becomes more somber*

But then... eight months ago, we started trying again. I got pregnant fairly quickly, actually—within a couple of months. I was so hopeful. But at about nine weeks, I started spotting. I went to the ER, and they did an ultrasound and confirmed it was a miscarriage. It was... it was really hard.

*She pauses, her voice becoming quieter*

That's when things shifted for us. After that loss, nothing has happened. We've been trying consistently for about four more months since then, and just... nothing. It's been frustrating and emotionally draining.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression shifts, becoming more contemplative*

Well, with Jacob and Lucas, I was pretty proactive. I think with Jacob, I called my OB-GYN's office the day after I got that positive home test. I was eager to get everything confirmed and get started on prenatal care. They got me in within about a week or so.

*She leans forward slightly*

My first appointment was pretty standard, I think. They did the usual blood work, urine tests, took my medical history. My doctor at the time was Dr. Patterson—she was wonderful, very thorough. I remember feeling reassured by how organized and professional everything was. She went over all the screening options, discussed nutrition, exercise, all of that. I felt well-informed.

*Her tone becomes warmer*

With Lucas, since I'd done it before, I knew what to expect. I called the office again right away, and the process was similar. By then, I'd switched to a different OB-GYN in the practice—Dr. Chen—and she was also very attentive.

*Her expression becomes more guarded*

But I have to be honest... the experience with the miscarriage was quite different. When I started spotting, I went to the emergency room at our regional hospital—it's about twenty minutes away from here in town. The staff there were clinical and efficient, but it felt... cold, I guess? They confirmed the miscarriage, gave me some information about what to expect physically, and sent me home. 

*She pauses, her voice becoming quieter*

They offered me information about follow-up care, but I felt a bit lost. I wish there had been more emotional support or counseling resources offered. It was just very matter-of-fact.

*She looks at you*

Since then, I haven't been pregnant again, so I haven't had that prenatal care experience recently. But now with the fertility concerns, I've been seeing my primary care doctor and we've discussed referrals to a fertility specialist.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily shifts in her chair, her expression becoming a bit more complex*

Well, right now, I'm not actually in prenatal care since I'm not currently pregnant. But let me explain the situation.

*She gestures thoughtfully*

For my previous pregnancies with Jacob and Lucas, I was under the care of Dr. Chen at the OB-GYN practice here in town—Riverside Women's Health. She's been my primary OB-GYN for the past several years, and I do have a good relationship with her. She's knowledgeable, listens well, and I felt comfortable with her during both pregnancies.

*Her tone becomes a bit more hesitant*

However, since we've been trying to conceive without success for the past year, and especially after the miscarriage, things have shifted a bit. Dr. Chen has been supportive, but honestly, I think we're reaching the limits of what she can do in a general OB-GYN practice. She's recommended that we see a fertility specialist, which is why we're now exploring that option.

*She pauses, looking a bit uncertain*

That's actually been one of the challenges. Finding a fertility specialist isn't as straightforward here in rural Ohio. The nearest reproductive endocrinologist is about forty-five minutes away in a larger city. So we're still in the process of getting that referral set up and scheduling an initial consultation.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

I think Dr. Chen cares about my wellbeing, but I can tell she's a bit outside her wheelhouse with fertility issues. She's been encouraging about pursuing specialist care, which I appreciate. But there's definitely been a gap in support between what a general OB-GYN can offer and what we actually need right now.

*She looks at you earnestly*

Does that make sense? It's been a bit of a journey trying to navigate the healthcare system, especially in a smaller town.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily pauses, then offers a clarifying smile*

Oh, I should clarify—since I'm not currently pregnant, I'm not having prenatal appointments right now. But I can definitely tell you what those visits were like during my pregnancies with Jacob and Lucas, since those are still pretty fresh in my memory.

*She settles back, organizing her thoughts*

During both pregnancies, the schedule was pretty standard, I think. In the first trimester, I'd go in about once a month. Then it increased to every two to three weeks in the second trimester, and by the third trimester, I was going in weekly, especially toward the end.

*She describes the routine with practiced familiarity*

A typical visit would go something like this: I'd check in at the front desk, fill out any necessary paperwork or updates. Then a nurse would take me back, check my blood pressure, weight, and ask about any symptoms or concerns since the last visit. They'd do a urine test—I think they were checking for protein and glucose.

*She continues*

Then Dr. Chen would come in. She'd ask how I was feeling, if I had any questions or concerns. She'd examine me—checking my abdomen, measuring fundal height as the pregnancy progressed. In the later visits, she'd also do cervical checks to see if there was any dilation or effacement.

*Her expression becomes more animated*

Around 20 weeks, there was the big ultrasound—the anatomy scan. That was exciting! We got to see the babies, confirm everything was developing normally. They checked all the organs, the placenta, amniotic fluid levels, all of that.

*She pauses thoughtfully*

I also had the standard screening tests—the glucose tolerance test around 28 weeks, which wasn't fun. And blood work for things like gestational diabetes screening, anemia checks, that sort of thing.

*Her tone becomes more reflective*

Honestly, both pregnancies were fairly routine. I never had any major complications, so the visits were pretty straightforward. Dr. Chen was always thorough but efficient. She'd answer my questions, give me educational materials about what to expect at each stage, discuss nutrition and exercise.

*She looks at you*

The visits felt supportive and professional. I felt like my concerns were being taken seriously, and I always left feeling more informed about my pregnancy and what to expect next.

*She adds with a slight note of wistfulness*

It's quite different now, being in this limbo where I'm not pregnant but desperately want to be. The appointments I'm having now are more... diagnostic and exploratory, rather than the reassuring routine of prenatal care.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily considers the question carefully, her expression becoming more thoughtful*

Well, as I mentioned, both of my pregnancies with Jacob and Lucas were relatively uncomplicated. I was fortunate in that regard. But I do want to be thorough about this.

*She shifts slightly, organizing her thoughts*

During both pregnancies, I experienced typical first-trimester morning sickness—nausea and some vomiting, particularly in the mornings, though it did ease up by around week 14 or so. Nothing severe enough to require hospitalization or IV fluids, thankfully.

*She continues more deliberately*

I also dealt with fatigue, especially in the first and third trimesters. By the end of both pregnancies, I was pretty exhausted—which I think is pretty normal when you're carrying extra weight and dealing with hormonal changes.

*Her expression becomes more serious*

Now, there is something I should mention that's in my health history—I have chronic low back pain. It's been an issue for me for several years, actually. During my pregnancies, that definitely got worse. The weight gain and postural changes of pregnancy really aggravated it. By the third trimester with both boys, I was having significant lower back discomfort. I did physical therapy exercises and wore a maternity support belt, which helped somewhat.

*She pauses, her tone becoming more somber*

As for the miscarriage eight months ago... that was the most significant complication I've experienced. As I mentioned, I started spotting around nine weeks. I went to the ER, and they confirmed it was a miscarriage—the fetus had stopped developing. They explained my options: I could wait for it to pass naturally, take medication to help it along, or have a D&C procedure.

*Her voice becomes quieter*

I chose to let it pass naturally, which took about a week. It was physically painful—cramping, heavier bleeding than a normal period. And emotionally, it was devastating. I took a week off work, which was difficult because I felt like I had to explain myself to my principal, even though it's a private medical matter.

*She looks at you with vulnerability*

After the miscarriage, I had some follow-up bleeding and cramping for a couple of weeks. Dr. Chen did a follow-up ultrasound to make sure everything had passed completely. Physically, I recovered. But emotionally... that took longer.

*She adds thoughtfully*

The medical team didn't really screen me for postpartum depression or grief counseling after the miscarriage, which I think would have been helpful. I kind of had to work through it on my own, with support from Mark and a couple of close friends.

*Her expression becomes more matter-of-fact*

Other than that, I haven't had any other major health complications during pregnancy. No gestational diabetes, no preeclampsia, no placental issues. I was fortunate in that way.

*She pauses*

Though I do wonder sometimes if there's something underlying that we haven't discovered yet—something that might explain why I can't conceive now after having two successful pregnancies. That's part of why we're pursuing the fertility specialist evaluation.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily nods, thinking through her current regimen*

Right now, since I'm not pregnant, my medication list is fairly minimal, actually.

*She counts on her fingers*

For my chronic low back pain, I take ibuprofen as needed—usually a couple of times a week when it flares up. Nothing prescription-strength. I've tried to manage it with physical therapy exercises and good posture, especially since I'm hoping to get pregnant soon. I've been hesitant to take anything stronger or more regularly given that we're trying to conceive.

*She continues*

I also take a prenatal vitamin daily—have been for the past year, actually, since we started actively trying to conceive. It's a standard over-the-counter prenatal with folic acid, iron, calcium, and other vitamins. My OB-GYN recommended I start taking it even before getting pregnant, which made sense to me.

*She pauses thoughtfully*

Beyond that, I don't take any other medications regularly. I'm not on any birth control or anything like that, obviously. I don't have any chronic conditions that require daily medications—no blood pressure issues, no thyroid problems, nothing like that.

*Her tone becomes a bit more hesitant*

As for supplements, I've been pretty conservative. Just the prenatal vitamin, really. Though I'll admit, I've been tempted to try some of the fertility supplements I've seen online—CoQ10, vitex, that sort of thing. But I haven't started any of those yet. I wanted to talk to the fertility specialist first before adding anything else to my routine.

*She looks at you*

Is there something specific you're asking about, or are you just getting a complete picture of what I'm taking?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression becomes more engaged, as if discussing a topic she's given considerable thought to*

Oh yes, nutrition was something I was pretty intentional about during my pregnancies. I think being a teacher, I'm naturally inclined toward planning and structure, so I tried to apply that to my diet as well.

*She settles back, speaking thoughtfully*

During both pregnancies with Jacob and Lucas, I tried to eat a balanced diet. I focused on getting plenty of protein—chicken, fish, eggs, dairy products like yogurt and cheese. I knew that was important for fetal development.

*She continues with more detail*

I also made sure to eat lots of vegetables and fruits. I was particular about getting leafy greens for the folate, which I knew was important, especially in the first trimester. Spinach salads, broccoli, that sort of thing. And I tried to include whole grains rather than refined carbohydrates—whole wheat bread, brown rice, oatmeal.

*Her tone becomes more reflective*

I'll be honest though—the first trimester was challenging. The morning sickness made it hard to eat healthily sometimes. There were days when all I could stomach was crackers, ginger ale, and bland foods. I felt a bit guilty about that, but my doctor reassured me that it was normal and that once I got through that phase, I could focus more on nutrition.

*She shifts slightly*

By the second and third trimesters, I had more appetite and was able to be more intentional. I made sure to include calcium-rich foods—milk, yogurt, cheese—for bone development. I ate iron-rich foods like lean red meat and fortified cereals to prevent anemia. I also limited caffeine, which wasn't too hard for me since I'm not a huge coffee drinker anyway.

*Her expression becomes more cautious*

I was careful about food safety too. No deli meats, no unpasteurized dairy, no raw fish or undercooked meat. I know those are the recommendations, and I wanted to follow them carefully.

*She pauses*

As for weight gain, I gained about 30-35 pounds with each pregnancy, which my doctor said was appropriate for my pre-pregnancy weight and height. I tried to gain it gradually and steadily rather than all at once.

*Her tone becomes more thoughtful*

Now, since we've been trying to conceive again, I've been trying to maintain a healthy diet even though I'm not pregnant. I figure it can only help with fertility. I'm still taking my prenatal vitamin, eating plenty of fruits and vegetables, getting adequate protein. I've read that maintaining a healthy weight and good nutrition can support fertility, so I'm being mindful of that.

*She adds with a slight smile*

Though I'll admit, after the miscarriage, I had a period where I didn't care as much about eating well. I was emotional and just ate whatever was comforting. But I've gotten back on track since then.

*She looks at you*

Is there anything specific about nutrition during pregnancy you wanted to know more about?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression becomes noticeably more vulnerable, and she takes a moment before responding*

Well, as I mentioned, I'm not currently pregnant, but I can definitely speak to how I felt emotionally during my previous pregnancies, and also how I'm feeling now while we're trying to conceive.

*She pauses, choosing her words carefully*

During my pregnancies with Jacob and Lucas, I was... I was happy, mostly. Excited. There's something special about being pregnant—you're creating life, and that's profound. I felt this sense of purpose and anticipation.

*Her voice becomes softer*

But I'd be lying if I said there weren't some anxieties mixed in there too. Especially with Jacob, since it was my first pregnancy, I worried about whether everything was developing normally. Every little ache or pain, I'd wonder if something was wrong. I remember being nervous before each ultrasound, just hoping to see that heartbeat and know everything was okay.

*She continues more thoughtfully*

With Lucas, I was a bit more relaxed since I'd done it before and knew what to expect. But there's always that underlying anxiety, I think—the worry that something could go wrong, even when you're doing everything right.

*Her expression becomes noticeably more somber*

The emotional experience after the miscarriage, though... that was a completely different story. It was devastating. I felt this overwhelming sense of loss and grief. I kept replaying things in my mind—wondering if I'd done something wrong, if there was something I could have prevented.

*Her voice becomes quieter, more emotional*

I felt guilt, even though logically I know miscarriages aren't usually the mother's fault. But emotionally, I couldn't help but wonder: Did I exercise too hard? Was I stressed? Did I eat something I shouldn't have? It was irrational, but those thoughts were there.

*She pauses, visibly composing herself*

I also felt a deep sadness. I'd already started imagining this baby—what they might look like, what their personality might be like. And then suddenly, that was gone. It took me weeks to stop crying randomly throughout the day.

*Her tone becomes more vulnerable*

What made it harder was that I felt like I had to keep it together for Jacob and Lucas. I couldn't just fall apart because they needed me to be their mom and be present for them. So I was grieving privately, trying to function normally at work and at home, and that was exhausting.

*She looks at you earnestly*

The hardest part was that nobody really talked about it much after the initial diagnosis. My doctor gave me medical information, but there wasn't much emotional support offered. My family and friends were sympathetic, but I think they didn't quite know what to say, so after a while, it felt like nobody wanted to talk about it anymore. But I was still processing it.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

And now, this past year of trying to conceive without success... that's brought up a whole different set of emotions. There's hope every month when we might be getting close to ovulation. Then there's disappointment when my period comes. And there's this underlying anxiety—is something wrong with me? Will I ever be able to have another baby?

*She pauses, her voice becoming quieter*

I've noticed I'm more emotional than I used to be. Little things upset me more easily. I see pregnant women or families with three or more kids, and I feel this pang of envy mixed with sadness. It's not a feeling I'm proud of, but it's there.

*She continues with vulnerability*

Mark has been supportive, but I can tell he's frustrated too. We don't talk about it as much as we probably should. There's this unspoken tension around it—this thing we both want but can't seem to make happen.

*Her tone becomes more introspective*

I've also felt some isolation, honestly. Most of my friends already have their families complete, or they didn't struggle with conception. So I don't have many people who really understand what this feels like. It's lonely sometimes.

*She looks at you with a mix of sadness and determination*

I haven't sought out professional mental health support, though I'm wondering if I should. Part of me feels like I should just be able to handle this on my own, but another part of me recognizes that this has been emotionally taxing. Does that... does that seem like something I should be doing?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression softens, and she seems to take some comfort in this question*

That's a good question. I do have support, though I'll admit it's not always as robust as I might wish, especially now during this difficult time.

*She begins thoughtfully*

First and foremost, there's Mark, my husband. He's been my primary support system. He was there through both pregnancies, came to appointments when he could, was present for both deliveries. He's been wonderful about that.

*Her tone becomes warmer but also more complicated*

During the pregnancies, he was attentive—rubbing my back when it hurt, helping me with physical tasks as I got bigger, being excited about the babies. After the miscarriage, he was there for me emotionally too, though I think we both struggled with it in our own ways. We didn't always talk about it as much as we probably should have.

*She pauses*

Right now, with the fertility struggles, I think he's trying to be supportive, but there's this underlying tension. We're both grieving the baby we lost and frustrated about not conceiving again. Sometimes I feel like we're just going through the motions rather than really connecting about it.

*She continues, shifting to other relationships*

My parents live about thirty minutes away. They've been helpful, especially with childcare when I've had medical appointments. My mom was very supportive during my pregnancies—she'd call to check on me, offer advice. After the miscarriage, she was sympathetic, though I don't think she fully understood the emotional weight of it. She had her kids easily, so she didn't have experience with loss or infertility.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

I have a couple of close friends here in town—Sarah and Jennifer. We've known each other since college. They were excited about my pregnancies and supportive in their own ways. But honestly, after the miscarriage, I felt like the conversation kind of... faded. They didn't know what to say, I think, and I didn't want to keep bringing it up and making things awkward.

*She pauses, her voice becoming quieter*

Now, with the fertility struggles, I haven't really opened up to them about it. Part of me is embarrassed, I guess. Like, why should I be struggling when I've already had two kids? And part of me just doesn't want to talk about it because it feels like complaining or seeking pity.

*Her tone becomes more thoughtful*

At work, I have colleagues I'm friendly with, but I haven't shared much about what's going on personally. Teaching is demanding, and I try to keep my professional life separate from my personal struggles. Though I will say, when I took that week off after the miscarriage, I had to give my principal some explanation, which felt invasive.

*She continues with a hint of vulnerability*

I'm part of a church community here in town, and that's been somewhat supportive. We have a women's group that meets monthly. They've been kind, but again, I haven't really opened up about the infertility struggles. There's still some stigma around that, I think.

*Her expression becomes more introspective*

Honestly, I think one of my biggest challenges right now is that I'm not getting specialized emotional support. I have people who care about me, but nobody who really understands what I'm going through. That's part of why I'm here, I suppose—hoping that this research and potentially connecting with a fertility specialist will help me feel less alone in this.

*She looks at you with a mix of hope and sadness*

I've thought about looking into support groups for people dealing with infertility or pregnancy loss, but I haven't taken that step yet. Part of me worries about the time commitment, and part of me is just not sure if that's the right move.

*She pauses*

Do you think that would be helpful? I mean, connecting with others going through similar experiences?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression becomes a bit uncertain, and she tilts her head thoughtfully*

Well, that's an interesting question given my current situation. Since I'm not pregnant right now, I haven't really started thinking about a birth plan yet. But I can certainly tell you about my experiences with my previous deliveries and what I learned from those.

*She settles back, speaking from experience*

With both Jacob and Lucas, I had vaginal deliveries, and both went fairly smoothly. I didn't have a formal written birth plan, to be honest—I was a first-time mom with Jacob, so I was just kind of... going with the flow and trusting my doctor's guidance. By the time I had Lucas, I had a better sense of what to expect, but I still didn't sit down and write out a detailed plan.

*Her tone becomes more reflective*

Looking back, I think I would have benefited from being more intentional about that. There were aspects of both deliveries that I didn't have as much control over as I might have liked.

*She continues more thoughtfully*

With Jacob, I labored at home for a while, which was nice. I could move around, take a shower, be in my own space. When we went to the hospital, I was pretty far along. I wanted to try to labor without an epidural initially, but after several hours of active labor, I got an epidural for pain management. That was fine—it helped me rest a bit. The delivery itself was straightforward. I pushed for maybe 45 minutes, and he was born.

*Her expression becomes warmer at the memory*

With Lucas, labor progressed faster. We got to the hospital and I was already quite far along. I did get an epidural again, though I was less certain about it that time. But it made the experience more manageable. His delivery was quicker—maybe 30 minutes of pushing.

*She pauses, her tone becoming more considered*

If I were to get pregnant again—and I really hope I do—I think I'd want to be more intentional about my birth preferences. I'd probably want to:

*She counts on her fingers*

First, I'd want to labor as naturally as possible for as long as I can manage, without immediately jumping to medical interventions. I liked being able to move around and change positions during labor.

Second, I'd want to limit unnecessary interventions—no induction unless medically necessary, no continuous fetal monitoring unless there's a reason for it. I know some of that is standard, but I'd want to discuss options.

*Her voice becomes more thoughtful*

Third, I'd want Mark to be present throughout, which he was both times. That was really important to me.

*She continues*

As for pain management, I'm open to an epidural if I need it, but I'd like to try to progress as far as I can without one. With my chronic back pain, I'm a bit concerned about how that might affect labor, so I might need intervention sooner than someone without that issue.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

I'd also want immediate skin-to-skin contact with the baby after delivery if possible, and I'd want to breastfeed if I can. I breastfed both Jacob and Lucas, which was a positive experience overall, though it had its challenges in the beginning.

*She pauses*

I think I'd also want to discuss pain management options that don't involve an epidural—things like nitrous oxide, IV pain medication, or other alternatives. I'm not opposed to an epidural, but I'd like to know what other options are available.

*Her tone becomes more cautious*

Given my experience with the miscarriage and the lack of emotional support afterward, if I do get pregnant again and have another delivery, I'd want to make sure there's a plan for postpartum mental health screening. I'd want to be proactive about that rather than waiting to see if I develop postpartum depression.

*She looks at you with a mix of hope and uncertainty*

But honestly, right now, the birth plan feels like a distant hope. First, I need to get pregnant again. That's the immediate challenge we're facing.

*She adds with a slight smile*

Though I appreciate you asking about it. It does help me think about what I'd want if we're fortunate enough to have another baby.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily nods thoughtfully, seeming to appreciate the question*

Oh, I've used quite a few different sources over the years, actually. My approach has probably evolved since my first pregnancy.

*She settles back, organizing her thoughts*

With Jacob, I was pretty reliant on my OB-GYN, Dr. Patterson at the time. She gave me educational materials at each visit—pamphlets about what to expect at each trimester, nutrition guidelines, that sort of thing. I read those carefully.

*Her tone becomes more animated*

I also bought a couple of pregnancy books. I remember reading "What to Expect When You're Expecting"—that was kind of the standard back then. It was helpful for understanding the timeline of development and what symptoms were normal versus concerning. I also looked at some online resources, though I was more cautious about that back then. The internet felt less reliable to me at the time.

*She continues*

I talked to my mom and my friends who had kids. That was actually really valuable—hearing their experiences, their advice, what they wished they'd known. That peer support was comforting.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

By the time I was pregnant with Lucas, I was more confident and didn't feel like I needed as much information. I still got the materials from Dr. Chen, and I'd reference them occasionally. I used online resources more by then—things like BabyCenter and What to Expect's website. Those had week-by-week updates about fetal development.

*She pauses*

I also watched some childbirth videos on YouTube, which I found helpful for understanding what labor and delivery might look like. Some were more clinical, others were more personal birth stories.

*Her tone becomes more cautious*

I'll be honest though—I also fell into the trap of Dr. Google sometimes. If I had a symptom or concern, I'd search it online and then worry about rare complications that probably weren't relevant to me. My doctor had to reassure me a few times that I was catastrophizing based on things I'd read online.

*She continues more thoughtfully*

After the miscarriage, I actually searched a lot online for information about miscarriage—what causes it, whether it was something I did, what the recovery process should look like. Some of that information was helpful, but a lot of it was either too clinical or too emotionally triggering. I wish I'd had better guidance on where to find reliable, compassionate information about pregnancy loss.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

Now, while we're dealing with infertility, I've been doing a lot more research. I've looked at fertility websites, read articles about causes of infertility, success rates of different treatments. I've also joined a couple of online forums for people struggling with conception, which has been... mixed. Some of it is really supportive and informative, but some of it is also anxiety-inducing because people share their worst-case scenarios.

*She pauses*

I've watched some TED talks and listened to podcasts about fertility and pregnancy loss. Those have been somewhat helpful for feeling less alone, hearing other people's stories.

*Her tone becomes more cautious*

I've also seen a lot of information on social media about fertility supplements, natural ways to improve conception, that sort of thing. Some of it seems credible, and some of it seems like pseudoscience. I'm trying to be discerning about what I believe and what I try.

*She continues*

I haven't really connected with a fertility counselor or therapist yet, but I've looked into whether that's available in our area. I've also thought about asking for recommendations from my doctor about reliable resources for infertility information.

*Her expression becomes more thoughtful*

I think my ideal would be a combination of things: reliable medical information from my healthcare providers, peer support from people going through similar experiences, and evidence-based resources that I can trust. Right now, I feel like I'm kind of cobbling together information from various sources and trying to figure out what's accurate and what's hype.

*She looks at you earnestly*

What would you recommend? Are there particular sources you'd suggest for someone in my situation?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression becomes more serious and thoughtful, and she takes a moment before responding*

That's a practical question, and honestly, it's something that's been on my mind quite a bit, especially now with the fertility treatments potentially on the horizon.

*She shifts in her chair*

With Jacob and Lucas, financially, we were in a fairly stable position. Mark and I both had jobs with steady income. We have private health insurance through my employer—I get it as a benefit of being a full-time teacher. That covered most of the prenatal care and hospital delivery costs, though we still had some out-of-pocket expenses for copays and deductibles.

*Her tone becomes more matter-of-fact*

I'd say our out-of-pocket costs for each pregnancy were probably around $2,000 to $3,000 total when you factor in all the copays, ultrasounds, and delivery. That was manageable for us, though it wasn't insignificant. We absorbed those costs, and it wasn't a huge burden, but it did require planning.

*She continues more thoughtfully*

We also had to budget for baby-related expenses—crib, car seat, clothes, diapers, formula eventually since I stopped breastfeeding after a few months with each. With our second baby, we were able to reuse a lot of items from Jacob, which helped financially.

*Her expression becomes more concerned*

Now, the fertility treatments are a different story, and that's been a source of stress for us. We've been looking into what a fertility specialist would cost, and it's... it's significant.

*She pauses, her voice becoming quieter*

From what I've researched, an initial consultation might be a few hundred dollars. Basic fertility testing—blood work, ultrasounds, semen analysis—could be another $1,000 to $2,000 out of pocket depending on what our insurance covers. And if we need more advanced treatments like IUI or IVF, we're talking thousands of dollars per cycle.

*Her tone becomes more anxious*

Our insurance does cover some fertility diagnostics, but I'm not sure about treatment coverage. I haven't actually looked at our policy in detail yet—that's something I need to do. I'm worried that fertility treatment might not be covered, or only partially covered.

*She continues with visible concern*

Mark and I have been talking about this, and there's definitely some financial anxiety. We're not wealthy. We're solidly middle-class, but we're not in a position where we can just throw thousands of dollars at fertility treatments without it affecting our budget. We have a mortgage, car payments, property taxes, all the usual expenses.

*Her expression becomes more conflicted*

We have some savings—maybe enough for one or two cycles of treatment if it came to that—but beyond that, we'd have to make some difficult choices. We could potentially take out a loan or use a credit card, but that would add debt, which is stressful.

*She pauses thoughtfully*

I've also thought about whether we should be pursuing fertility treatment at all, given the financial implications. Part of me wonders if we should just accept that maybe we're meant to have two children. But then I think about how much we want another baby, and it feels worth pursuing, at least initially.

*Her tone becomes more practical*

One thing I've been looking into is whether there are any grants or financial assistance programs for people struggling with infertility. I haven't found much in our area, but I know some fertility clinics offer payment plans or discounts for multiple cycles.

*She continues*

I've also thought about whether I could pick up extra work to help pay for treatment—tutoring, summer school, that sort of thing. Mark's mentioned possibly picking up overtime at the plant. But that would mean less time with our family, which is a trade-off.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

There's also the question of what happens if treatment doesn't work. Do we keep trying? At what point do we stop? Both of those decisions have financial implications, but they also have emotional and practical implications for our family.

*She looks at you with a mix of concern and determination*

I think what I'm saying is that while we're in a better financial position than a lot of people, fertility treatment is still a significant financial commitment for us. It's something we're taking seriously and trying to plan for, but it's also a source of stress and uncertainty.

*She pauses*

We haven't actually met with a fertility specialist yet to know what our actual costs would be, so a lot of this is speculation based on research I've done online. Once we have that consultation and understand what our insurance covers, we'll be in a better position to make informed decisions about how to proceed.

*Her tone becomes more vulnerable*

Honestly, the financial aspect is adding another layer of pressure to an already emotionally difficult situation. I wish fertility treatment were more affordable or more covered by insurance. It feels like it's only accessible to people with significant financial resources, and that's frustrating.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily's expression becomes more thoughtful, and she nods as if this is something she's reflected on before*

That's a good question. My work situation has definitely been affected by my reproductive health journey, though in different ways depending on the circumstances.

*She settles back, organizing her thoughts*

With Jacob and Lucas, I was able to continue teaching throughout both pregnancies, which I'm grateful for. Being a teacher actually gave me some flexibility that I might not have had in other jobs.

*Her tone becomes more reflective*

During the pregnancies themselves, I managed fairly well. I was teaching third grade, which is physically demanding—you're on your feet a lot, managing a classroom of active kids. By the third trimester, I was definitely tired and uncomfortable. My back pain got worse, as I mentioned. There were days when I'd come home absolutely exhausted.

*She continues*

My principal and colleagues were generally supportive. I didn't have to hide my pregnancy—it was obvious pretty quickly. Some of my colleagues who had kids were sympathetic about the physical challenges. I did have to modify some activities—I couldn't lift heavy boxes of materials, for instance. But overall, I was able to keep working right up until I went into labor.

*Her expression becomes more somber*

I took maternity leave after each birth—I think it was about 8 weeks with Jacob and 6 weeks with Lucas. That was covered under FMLA, which was helpful. It gave me time to recover physically and bond with the babies before returning to work.

*She pauses*

The challenge was that after my maternity leave ended, I had to return to full-time teaching while managing the demands of a newborn and an older sibling. That was... it was hard. I was exhausted. I was trying to be present for my students during the day, and then I'd come home and be a mom. Breastfeeding made it more complicated because I was pumping at work.

*Her tone becomes more vulnerable*

I remember feeling guilty—guilty that I wasn't fully present at work because I was thinking about my baby at home, and guilty that I wasn't fully present at home because I was thinking about my classroom. That's a common struggle for working mothers, I think, but it was real for me.

*She continues more thoughtfully*

Now, with the miscarriage and the subsequent fertility struggles, my work situation has been affected differently.

*Her voice becomes quieter*

When I had the miscarriage, I took a week off work. I had to notify my principal that I was having a medical emergency, though I didn't go into detail about what it was. I think she assumed it was something else—maybe appendicitis or another acute condition. I didn't volunteer information, and she didn't ask, which I appreciated.

*She pauses*

But taking that time off meant I had to leave detailed lesson plans for a substitute teacher, and when I came back, I had to catch my students up on what they'd missed. It was disruptive, and I felt like I had to explain myself without really wanting to share the details of my miscarriage with my workplace.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

Since then, the fertility struggles have been affecting my emotional state at work. I'm more irritable, more emotional, more easily upset by things. I'm worried that my colleagues might notice and ask questions. I'm also dealing with the monthly disappointment of not conceiving, which can affect my mood and energy levels.

*She continues with visible concern*

I've also been thinking about the logistics of fertility treatment. If we do proceed with a fertility specialist, there will be appointments—potentially multiple appointments—that I'll need to take time off work for. That's going to be tricky to manage. I can't exactly tell my principal, "I need to leave early for my fertility appointment," without sharing more than I'm comfortable with.

*Her tone becomes more anxious*

And if we do end up pursuing IVF or other intensive treatments, there could be significant time off needed—for procedures, for recovery, potentially for complications. I'm worried about how that will affect my job performance and how my employer will perceive it.

*She pauses thoughtfully*

There's also the question of what happens if I do get pregnant again. I'd want to take maternity leave again, which is my right, but I'm also aware that repeated absences for pregnancy and fertility-related issues might affect how I'm perceived professionally. I don't think it should, but I worry about it.

*Her expression becomes more conflicted*

I love my job. I love working with my students and being part of the school community. But right now, there's this tension between my professional responsibilities and my personal health needs. I'm trying to manage both, but it's not always easy.

*She looks at you earnestly*

I think what would help is if there were more workplace support for people dealing with fertility issues and pregnancy loss. More flexibility, more understanding, less stigma around taking time off for reproductive health. But that's not the reality I'm facing right now.

*Her tone becomes more determined*

I'm managing, though. I'm showing up, doing my job, trying to be present for my students. But I won't lie—it's taking emotional energy that I don't always have to spare.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*Emily pauses, her expression becoming a mix of hope and practical concern*

Well, as with the birth plan, this is something I haven't fully thought through yet since I'm not currently pregnant. But I can tell you about my experiences postpartum with Jacob and Lucas, and what I've learned from those.

*She settles back thoughtfully*

After Jacob was born, I was... I wasn't really prepared for what postpartum would be like, honestly. Nobody really talks about it in detail during pregnancy. I knew there would be recovery, bleeding, that sort of thing. But the emotional and physical reality was more intense than I expected.

*Her voice becomes more reflective*

Physically, I had significant bleeding for several weeks. I was sore, especially from the vaginal delivery. Sitting was uncomfortable. I had night sweats, which was strange and unsettling. My hormones were all over the place. And I was exhausted—that bone-deep exhaustion that comes from sleep deprivation with a newborn.

*She continues more thoughtfully*

Emotionally, I experienced what I think was postpartum depression, though I didn't recognize it as such at the time. I remember feeling overwhelmed, anxious, sometimes tearful for no clear reason. I was worried constantly that something was wrong with Jacob—was he eating enough? Was he sleeping too much? I'd check on him constantly.

*Her tone becomes more vulnerable*

I didn't talk to anyone about how I was feeling. I thought I was just supposed to be happy and grateful, so I kept it to myself. Looking back, I wish I'd reached out for help. It probably would have made those first few months easier.

*She pauses*

With Lucas, I was somewhat more prepared, but I still struggled. The postpartum period was similar—the physical recovery, the sleep deprivation, the emotional ups and downs. But because I'd been through it before, I recognized some of the signs of postpartum depression earlier. I still didn't seek professional help, but I was more aware of what was happening and tried to be gentler with myself.

*Her expression becomes more thoughtful*

Now, if I do get pregnant again and have another baby, I think I'd want to approach the postpartum period differently.

*She counts on her fingers*

First, I'd want to have a plan in place for mental health support. I'd want to know what screening looks like, what resources are available if I'm struggling emotionally. I'd probably want to consider working with a therapist or counselor postpartum, rather than waiting to see if depression develops.

*She continues*

Second, I'd want to plan for practical support. With Jacob and Lucas, Mark took some time off work after each birth—I think it was about a week or two. That was helpful. But then I was managing everything largely on my own during the day while he was at work. If I could do it again, I'd want to arrange for more support—maybe my mom coming to stay for a few weeks, or hiring some help for household tasks so I could focus on recovery and the baby.

*Her tone becomes more practical*

Third, I'd want to be more intentional about self-care during the postpartum period. With my previous babies, I kind of neglected myself because I was so focused on the baby. I didn't sleep when the baby slept because I was doing laundry or trying to catch up on other things. I ate irregularly. I didn't move my body much beyond the necessary activities. I think that contributed to how I was feeling emotionally.

*She pauses*

I'd also want to plan for breastfeeding support if I'm going to breastfeed again. With both boys, I struggled initially with latch and pain. It took several weeks to get comfortable. Having access to a lactation consultant earlier might have made that easier. I did eventually work through it and breastfed for several months, which I'm proud of, but the beginning was harder than it needed to be.

*Her expression becomes more reflective*

I'd also want to think about returning to work. With my previous babies, I returned after 6-8 weeks, which felt very soon. I wasn't physically or emotionally ready, but I felt like I had to be. If I could do it again, I'd want to advocate for a longer maternity leave if possible, or at least a phased return where I could work part-time initially.

*She continues thoughtfully*

And I'd want to plan for how to manage my chronic back pain postpartum. I was in a lot of pain after both deliveries, and I was limited in what I could do physically. I couldn't lift, couldn't bend easily, couldn't do the physical demands of caring for a newborn without pain. Physical therapy might have helped, but I didn't prioritize it during that time.

*Her tone becomes more vulnerable*

I think what I'm realizing is that I need to be more proactive about my own wellbeing during the postpartum period. It's not selfish to take care of myself—it actually makes me a better mother and partner because I'm not running on empty.

*She pauses*

I'd also want Mark and I to have a plan for how we're going to manage our relationship during this time. With both previous babies, we kind of went into survival mode. We weren't really connecting as a couple. By the time things normalized, we'd kind of drifted a bit. I'd want to be more intentional about maintaining our connection, even in small ways.

*Her expression becomes more hopeful but also cautious*

Of course, all of this is contingent on me actually getting pregnant again. Right now, that feels like the biggest hurdle. But yes, if I'm fortunate enough to have another baby, I want to approach the postpartum period with more awareness, more planning, and more self-compassion than I did the first two times.

*She looks at you earnestly*

Do you think it's important to plan for postpartum mental health support before pregnancy, or is that something that's typically addressed after delivery?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
